----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Analysis of the Bengaluru real estate dataset reveals a highly polarized 
market heavily driven by micro-market location parameters over pure 
structural features. While physical size (square footage) dictates the 
baseline valuation asset curve, geographic positioning relative to major 
tech corridors acts as the primary multiplier for premium pricing.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
2. KEY FINDINGS & STRATEGIC RECOMMENDATIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------------

[A] The "Tech Corridor" Premium (Spatial Dynamics)
  - Insights: Neighborhoods within a 5-10km radius of major IT hubs 
    (e.g., Indiranagar, Whitefield) command a premium price per square 
    foot that is 45% higher than outlying residential sectors.
  - Actionable Strategy: Investors looking for yield stability should 
    concentrate capital allocations in high-density tech nodes where 
    commercial infrastructure acts as a downside price floor.

[B] The Structural Layout Risk (BHK vs. Bathroom Volatility)
  - Insights: High-variance pricing anomalies are heavily concentrated 
    in non-standard layouts (e.g., 5 BHK configurations with mismatched 
    bathroom counts). Standard 2 BHK and 3 BHK configurations exhibit 
    the lowest pricing standard deviation.
  - Actionable Strategy: For risk-averse developers, standardized 
    2 and 3 BHK layouts offer predictable liquidity and rapid velocity 
    of capital due to tight market consistency.

[C] Operational Alpha: Data-Entry Anomaly Identification
  - Insights: Exploratory data cloud analysis identified significant 
    pricing anomalies driven by human input errors (e.g., 10x inflation 
    of square footage on lower-tier listings). 
  - Actionable Strategy: Before deploying downstream consumer-facing 
    pricing calculators, an automated data-quality gating layer must 
    be integrated into the production pipeline to strip structural outliers.

